# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cape-verdian-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The archipelago was uninhabited until the 15th century, when Portuguese explorers settled the islands, establishing one of the first European settlements in the tropics.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Its strategic position gave it a significant role in the transatlantic slave trade during the 16th and 17th centuries; the islands saw rapid economic growth driven by the trade of manufactured goods, rum, cloth for African slaves, ivory, and gold.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] By the mid 19th century, increased foreign competition, persistent drought, and the decline of the slave trade led to economic decline and emigration; Cape Verde gradually recovered as an important commercial centre and stopping point for major shipping routes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since the early 1990s, it has been a stable representative democracy and has remained one of the most developed and democratic countries in Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Lacking natural resources, its developing economy is mostly service-oriented, with a growing focus on tourism and foreign investment.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] With a population of around 530,000 (as of 2026), Cape Verde is among the least populous countries in Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The Cape Verdean people trace their ancestry primarily to West African populations, with additional contributions from early Portuguese settlers and other groups who came to the islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] A sizeable diaspora exists across the world, especially in the United States and Portugal, considerably outnumbering the inhabitants on the islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde is a member state of the African Union.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The official language is Portuguese, while the recognized national language is Cape Verdean Creole (Crioulo), which is spoken by the vast majority of the population.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As of the 2021 census, the most populous islands were Santiago (269,370) – which hosts the country's capital and largest city, Praia – São Vicente (74,016), Santo Antão (36,632), Fogo (33,519) and Sal (33,347).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The country is named after the Cap-Vert peninsula on the Senegalese coast.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The name *Cap-Vert*, in turn, comes from the Portuguese language *Cabo Verde* ('green cape'), the name given to it by Portuguese explorers in 1444, a few years before they came across the islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Historically, the name has been anglicised as Cape Verde.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2013, the country's delegation informed the United Nations that only *Cabo Verde* (Portuguese pronunciation: [ˈkabu ˈveɾdɨ] ⓘ ) and not other translations should be used for official purposes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The archipelago was formed approximately 40–50 million years ago during the Eocene epoch.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Before the arrival of Europeans, the Cape Verde Islands were uninhabited.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] They were discovered by Genoese and Portuguese navigators around 1456.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] According to Portuguese official records, the first discoveries were made by Genoa-born António de Noli, who was afterwards appointed governor of Cape Verde by Portuguese King Afonso V.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 1462, Portuguese settlers arrived at Santiago and founded a settlement they called Ribeira Grande.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Today it is called Cidade Velha ("Old City"), to distinguish it from Ribeira Grande.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The original Ribeira Grande was the first permanent European settlement in the tropics.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In the 16th century, the archipelago prospered from the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Pirates occasionally attacked the Portuguese settlements.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Francis Drake, an English privateer, twice sacked Ribeira Grande in 1585 when it was a part of the Iberian Union.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] After a French attack in 1712, the town declined in importance relative to nearby Praia, which became the capital in 1770.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The decline in the slave trade in the 19th century resulted in an economic crisis.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde's early prosperity slowly evaporated.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] However, the islands' position astride mid-Atlantic shipping lanes made Cape Verde an ideal location for re-supplying ships.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Because of its excellent harbour Mindelo, located on the island of São Vicente, the country became an important commercial centre.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Diplomat Edmund Roberts visited Cape Verde in 1832.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde was the first stop on Charles Darwin's voyage with HMS *Beagle* in 1832.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] With few natural resources and inadequate sustainable investment from the Portuguese, citizens grew increasingly dissatisfied with their colonial masters, who refused to provide the local authorities with more autonomy.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 1951, Portugal changed Cape Verde's status from a colony to an overseas province in an attempt to blunt growing nationalism.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 1956, Amílcar Cabral and a group of fellow Cape Verdeans and Guineans organized (in Portuguese Guinea) the clandestine African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde (PAIGC).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It demanded improvement in economic, social, and political conditions in Cape Verde and Portuguese Guinea and formed the basis of the two nations' independence movement.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Its objective was to achieve independence through nonviolent protest.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] However, in 1959, the Portuguese authorities reacted with repression, marked by violence and mass arrests, persuading the PAIGC that armed struggle was the only viable means to overthrow the colonial regime.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Moving its headquarters to Conakry, Guinea, in 1960, the PAIGC began an armed rebellion against Portugal in 1961.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Acts of sabotage eventually grew into a war in Portuguese Guinea that pitted 10,000 PAIGC soldiers against 35,000 Portuguese and African troops.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] By 1972, the PAIGC controlled much of Portuguese Guinea despite the presence of the Portuguese troops, but the organization did not attempt to disrupt Portuguese control in Cape Verde.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Portuguese Guinea declared independence in 1973 and was granted *de jure* independence in 1974.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] A budding independence movement originally led by Amílcar Cabral, who was assassinated in 1973, passed on to his half-brother Luís Cabral and culminated in independence for the archipelago in 1975.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Following the April 1974 revolution in Portugal, the PAIGC became an active political movement in Cape Verde.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In December 1974, the PAIGC and Portugal signed an agreement providing for a transitional government composed of Portuguese and Cape Verdeans.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] On 30 June 1975, Cape Verdeans elected a National Assembly which received instruments of independence from Portugal on 5 July 1975.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] On 2 February 2024, Cape Verde became the third African country to be free of malaria.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde is a stable semi-presidential representative democratic republic.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2026, it was a joint second most democratic nation in Africa (alongside Mauritius and South Africa), ranking 40th in the world, according to the electoral democracy score of the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The constitution – adopted in 1980 and revised in 1992, 1995 and 1999 – defines the basic principles of its government.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The president is the head of state and is elected by popular vote for a five-year term.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The prime minister is the head of government and proposes other ministers and secretaries of state.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The prime minister is nominated by the National Assembly and appointed by the president.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Members of the National Assembly are elected by popular vote for five-year terms.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2016, three parties held seats in the National Assembly – MpD (36), PAICV (25), and the Cape Verdean Independent Democratic Union (UCID) (3).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The two main political parties are PAICV and MpD.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The judicial system consists of a Supreme Court of Justice – whose members are appointed by the president, the National Assembly, and the Board of the Judiciary – and regional courts.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Separate courts hear civil, constitutional, and criminal cases.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde follows a policy of nonalignment and seeks cooperative relations with all friendly states.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Angola, Brazil, China, Libya, Cuba, France, Guinea-Bissau, Germany, Italy, Portugal, Spain, São Tomé and Príncipe, Senegal, Russia, Luxembourg, and the United States maintain embassies in Praia.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde maintains a vigorously active foreign policy especially in Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde is a founding member state of the Community of Portuguese Language Countries, also known as the Lusophone Commonwealth, an international organization and political association of Lusophone nations across four continents, where Portuguese is an official language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde has bilateral relations with some Lusophone nations and holds membership in a number of international organizations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It also participates in most international conferences on economic and political issues.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since 2007, Cape Verde has a *special partnership* status with the EU, under the Cotonou Agreement, and might apply for special membership, in particular because the Cape Verdean escudo, the country's currency, is indexed to the euro.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2011 Cape Verde ratified the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2017 Cape Verde signed the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In November 2021, Cape Verde opened its first embassy in Nigeria.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The military of Cape Verde consists of the National Guard and the Coast Guard; 0.7% of the country's GDP was spent on the military in 2005.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Having fought their only battles in the war for independence against Portugal between 1974 and 1975, the efforts of the Cape Verdean armed forces have turned to combatting international drug trafficking.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2007, together with the Cape Verdean Police, they carried out Operation Flying Launch (*Operacão Lancha Voadora*), a successful operation to put an end to a drug trafficking group which smuggled cocaine from Colombia to the Netherlands and Germany using the country as a reorder point.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The operation took more than three years, being a secret operation during the first two years, and ended in 2010.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2016, Cape Verdean Armed Forces were involved in the Monte Tchota massacre, a green-on-green incident that resulted in 11 deaths.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The Cape Verde archipelago is in the Atlantic Ocean, approximately 570 kilometres (350 mi) off the western coast of the African continent, near Senegal, The Gambia, and Mauritania as well as part of the Macaronesia ecoregion.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It lies between latitudes 14° and 18°N, and longitudes 22° and 26°W.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The country is a horseshoe-shaped cluster of ten islands (nine inhabited) and eight islets, that constitute an area of 4033 km2 (1557 sq mi).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The largest island, both in size and population, is Santiago, which hosts the nation's capital, Praia, the principal urban agglomeration in the archipelago.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Sal, Boa Vista, and Maio, are fairly flat, sandy, and dry; the other islands are generally rockier with more vegetation.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Geologically, the islands are principally composed of igneous rocks, with volcanic structures and pyroclastic debris comprising the majority of the archipelago's total volume.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The volcanic and plutonic rocks are distinctly basic; the archipelago is a soda-alkaline petrographic province, with a petrologic succession similar to that found in other Macaronesian islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The islands lie on a bathymetric swell known as the Cape Verde Rise.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The rise is one of the largest protuberances in the world's oceans, rising 2.2 kilometres (1.4 miles) in a semi-circular region of 1200 km2 (460 sq mi), associated with a rise of the geoid.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Magnetic anomalies identified in the vicinity of the archipelago indicate that the structures forming the islands date back 125–150 million years: the islands date from 8 million (in the west) to 20 million years (in the east).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The oldest exposed rocks occurred on Maio and the northern peninsula of Santiago and are 128–131 million-year-old pillow lavas.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The first stage of volcanism in the islands began in the early Miocene and reached its peak at the end of this period when the islands reached their maximum sizes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Historical volcanism (within human settlement) has been restricted to Fogo.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Pico do Fogo, the largest active volcano in the region, erupted in 2014.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It has an eight-kilometre-diameter (five-mile) caldera, the rim of which is at an elevation of 1,600 metres (5,249 feet) and an interior cone that rises to 2,829 metres (9,281 feet) above sea level.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The caldera resulted from subsidence, following the partial evacuation (eruption) of the magma chamber, along a cylindrical column from within the magma chamber (at a depth of 8 kilometres (5 miles)).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Extensive salt flats are found on Sal and Maio.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] On Santiago, Santo Antão, and São Nicolau, arid slopes give way in places to sugarcane fields or banana plantations spread along the base of towering mountains.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Ocean cliffs have been formed by catastrophic debris landslides.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde's climate is milder than that of the African mainland because the surrounding sea moderates temperatures, and cold Atlantic currents produce an arid atmosphere.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Conversely, the islands do not receive the upwelling (cold streams) that affect the West African coast, so the air temperature is cooler than in Senegal, but the sea is warmer.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Because of the relief of some islands, such as Santiago with its steep mountains, the islands can have orographically induced precipitation, allowing rich woods and luxuriant vegetation to grow where the humid air condenses, soaking the plants, rocks, soil, logs, moss, etc.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] On the higher islands and somewhat wetter islands, the climate is suitable for the development of dry monsoon forests and laurel forests.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde lies in the Cape Verde Islands dry forests ecoregion.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Average temperatures range from 22 °C (72 °F) in February to 27 °C (80.6 °F) in September.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde is part of the Sahelian semi-arid belt, with nothing like the rainfall levels of nearby West Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It rains irregularly between August and October, with frequent brief heavy downpours.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] A desert is usually defined as terrain that receives less than 250 mm (9.8 in) of annual rainfall.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Sal's total of 145 mm (5.7 in) confirms this classification.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Most of the year's rain falls in September.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Because of the infrequent occurrence of rainfall where not mountainous, the landscape is so arid that less than two percent of it is arable.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Most rainfall precipitation is due to condensation of the ocean mist.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In some islands, like Santiago, the wetter climate of the interior and the eastern coast contrasts with the drier one on the south/southwest coast.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Western Hemisphere-bound hurricanes often have their early beginnings near the Cape Verde Islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] These Cape Verde hurricanes can become very intense as they cross warm Atlantic waters.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The average hurricane season has about two Cape Verde-type hurricanes, which are usually the largest and most intense storms of the season because they often have plenty of warm open ocean over which to develop before encountering land.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The five largest Atlantic tropical cyclones on record have been Cape Verde-type hurricanes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Most of the longest-lived tropical cyclones in the Atlantic basin are Cape Verde hurricanes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since 1851 the islands have been twice struck by hurricanes: in 1892 and in 2015 (Hurricane Fred, the easternmost hurricane ever to form in the Atlantic).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] According to the president of Nauru, in 2011, Cape Verde was ranked the eighth most endangered nation due to flooding from climate change.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2023, UN Secretary-General António Guterres arrived in Cabo Verde to raise concerns about climate change.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] He said that the country is on the frontlines of the existential crisis generated by climate disruptions and that world leaders need to take action to address the climate crisis.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cabo Verde is a leader in renewable energy in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As of 2023, 20% of its energy comes from renewable sources, and the goal is to increase that to 50% by 2030.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2023, Portugal signed an agreement to forgive €140 million of Cape Verde's debt in exchange for the country investing in environmental projects.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] This agreement is one of the first debt-for-nature swaps in Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde's isolation has resulted in the islands having several endemic species, particularly birds and reptiles, many of which are endangered by human development.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Endemic birds include Alexander's swift (*Apus alexandri*), Bourne's heron (*Ardea purpurea bournei*), the Raso lark (*Alauda razae*), the Cape Verde warbler (*Acrocephalus brevipennis*), and the Iago sparrow (*Passer iagoensis*).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The islands are also an important breeding area for seabirds including the Cape Verde shearwater.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Reptiles include the Cape Verde giant gecko (*Tarentola gigas*).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Forest cover is around 11% of the total land area, equivalent to 45,720 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 15,380 ha in 1990.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 13,680 ha and planted forest covered 32,040 ha.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde's notable economic growth and improvement in living conditions despite a lack of natural resources have garnered international recognition, with other countries and international organisations often providing development aid.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since 2007, the UN has classified it as a developing nation rather than a least developed country.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Only five of the ten main islands (Santiago, Santo Antão, São Nicolau, Fogo, and Brava) normally support significant agricultural production, and over 90% of all food consumed is imported.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Mineral resources include salt, pozzolana (a volcanic rock used in cement production), and limestone.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Its small number of wineries making Portuguese-style wines have traditionally focused on the domestic market, but have recently met with some international acclaim.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The economy is service-oriented, with commerce, transport, and public services accounting for more than 70% of the GDP.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Although nearly 35% of the population lives in rural areas, agriculture and fishing contribute only about 9% of GDP.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Light manufacturing accounts for most of the remainder.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Fish and shellfish are plentiful, and small quantities are exported.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde has cold storage and freezing facilities and fish processing plants in Mindelo, Praia, and on Sal.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Expatriate Cape Verdeans contribute an amount estimated at 20% of GDP to the domestic economy through remittances.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Despite having few natural resources and being semi-desert, the country has the highest living standards in the region and has attracted thousands of immigrants of different nationalities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since 1991, the government has pursued market-oriented economic policies, including an open welcome to foreign investors and a far-reaching privatization programme.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It established as top development priorities the promotion of a market economy and the private sector; the development of tourism, light manufacturing industries, and fisheries; and the development of transport, communications, and energy facilities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] From 1994 to 2000 about $407 million in foreign investments were made or planned, of which 58% were in tourism, 17% in industry, 4% in infrastructure, and 21% in fisheries and services.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2011, a wind farm was built on four islands that supplies about 30% of the electricity of the country.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As host to the ECOWAS Regional Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency, inaugurated in 2010, Cape Verde had planned to lead by example by becoming entirely reliant on renewable energy sources by 2025.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] This policy was consistent with the host of documents adopted in 2015 paving the way to more sustainable development, including Cape Verde's *Transformational Agenda to 2030*, its *National Renewable Energy Plan* and its *Low Carbon and Climate-resilient Development Strategy*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Two years later, these were followed by a *Strategic Plan for Sustainable Development, 2017–2021*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since then, Cape Verde has pushed back this goal, aiming for 50% of energy produced by renewable sources by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Between 2000 and 2009, real GDP increased on average by over 7% a year, well above the average for sub-Saharan countries and faster than most small island economies in the region.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Strong economic performance was bolstered by one of the fastest-growing tourism industries in the world, as well as by substantial capital inflows that allowed Cape Verde to build up national currency reserves to the current 3.5 months of imports.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Unemployment has been falling rapidly, and the country is on track to achieve most of the UN Millennium Development Goals – including halving its 1990 poverty level.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2007, Cape Verde joined the World Trade Organization (WTO) and in 2008 the country graduated from Least Developed Country (LDC) to Middle Income Country (MIC) status.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde has significant cooperation with Portugal at every level of the economy, which has led it to link its currency first to the Portuguese escudo and, in 1999, to the euro.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] On 23 June 2008 Cape Verde became the 153rd member of the WTO.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In early January 2018, the government announced that the minimum wage would be raised to 13,000 CVE (€118) per month, from 11,000 CVE, which was effective in mid-January 2018.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The European Commission's total allocation for the period of 2008–2013 foreseen for Cape Verde to address "poverty reduction, in particular in rural and peri-urban areas where women are heading the households, as well as good governance" amounts to €54.1 million.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde's strategic location at the crossroads of mid-Atlantic air and sea lanes has been enhanced by significant improvements at Mindelo's harbour (Porto Grande) and at Sal's and Praia's international airports.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Aristides Pereira International Airport was opened in 2007, and Cesária Évora Airport was opened in 2009.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Ship repair facilities at Mindelo were opened in 1983.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The major ports are Mindelo and Praia, but all other islands have smaller port facilities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In addition to the international airport on Sal, airports have been built on all of the inhabited islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] All but the airports on Brava and Santo Antão enjoy scheduled air service.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The archipelago has 3,050 km (1,895 mi) of roads, of which 1,010 km (628 mi) are paved, most using cobblestone.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde had a population of 491,233 in 2021.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] A large proportion (236,000) of Cape Verdeans live on Santiago.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verdeans are descendants of Africans (free or enslaved) and Europeans of various origins.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] There are also Cape Verdeans who have Jewish ancestors from North Africa, mainly on Boa Vista, Santiago, and Santo Antão.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The country's historical trajectory included, from the beginning, a process of social class formation.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] At this moment, the absence of a "bourgeoisie" can be seen, but the existence of several types of "petty bourgeoisie" is numerically significant.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The majority of the population is, however, made up of the peasantry and some working class.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It is the language of instruction and government.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] It is also used in newspapers, television, and radio.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verdean Creole (*Kriolu*) is used colloquially and is the mother tongue of virtually all Cape Verdeans.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The national constitution calls for measures to give it parity with Portuguese.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] There is a substantial body of literature in Creole, especially in the Santiago Creole and the São Vicente Creole.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] *Kriolu* has been gaining prestige since the nation's independence from Portugal.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The differences between the forms of the language within the islands have been a major obstacle to the standardization of the language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Some people have advocated the development of two standards: a north (Barlavento) standard, centred on the São Vicente Creole, and a south (Sotavento) standard, centred on the Santiago Creole.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Manuel Veiga, a linguist and minister of culture of Cape Verde, is the premier proponent of *Kriolu*'s officialization and standardization.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The vast majority of Cape Verdeans are Christian; reflecting centuries of Portuguese rule, Catholics make up the single largest religious community, at just under 80 percent, as of 2010 (slightly down from 85 percent of the population in 2007).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Judaism had a historical presence during the colonial era.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Atheists constitute less than 1 percent of the population.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Many Cape Verdeans syncretize Christianity with indigenous African beliefs and customs.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Almost twice as many Cape Verdeans live abroad (nearly one million) as in the country itself.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The islands have a long history of emigration, and Cape Verdeans are widely dispersed worldwide, from Macau to Haiti and Argentina to Sweden.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The diaspora may be much larger than official statistics indicate, as, until independence in 1975, Cape Verdean immigrants had Portuguese passports.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The majority live in the United States and Western Europe, with the former hosting the largest overseas population at 500,000.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Most in the U.S. are concentrated in New England, particularly Boston, New Bedford, and Providence; Brockton, Massachusetts, has the largest community of any American city (18,832).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verdeans have been migrating to Massachusetts since the 1840s, but most of the current population arrived in the 1970s.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] They are now one of the top ten immigrant groups in Boston and the largest African national group.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The first wave of immigrants came to Massachusetts to work in the whaling industry.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] When whaling declined, they moved into maritime jobs, seasonal agricultural work (like picking cranberries), and factory work.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The second wave of immigrants arrived after Cape Verde gained independence in 1975.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] They also found work in factories, but as manufacturing plants closed down, they moved into the service industry in the 1990s.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Immigrants have developed a vibrant small business sector, including restaurants, groceries, real estate and insurance offices, and other enterprises.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Immigrants in the U.S. have a long history of service in the U.S. military, with a presence in every major conflict from the Revolutionary War to the Vietnam War.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Due to centuries of colonial ties, the second largest number of Cape Verdeans live in Portugal (150,000), with sizeable communities in the former Portuguese colonies of Angola (45,000) and São Tomé and Príncipe (25,000).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Major populations exist in countries with cultural and linguistic similarities, such as Spain (65,500), France (25,000), Senegal (25,000), and Italy (20,000).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Other countries with large communities include the United Kingdom (35,500), the Netherlands (20,000, of which 15,000 are concentrated in Rotterdam), and Luxembourg and Scandinavia (7,000).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Outside the U.S. and Europe, the biggest Cape Verdean populations are in Mexico (5,000) and Argentina (8,000).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Over the years, Cape Verde has increasingly become a net recipient of migrants due to its relatively high per capita income, political and social stability, and civil liberties.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Migrants from China make up a sizeable and important segment of the foreign population, while nearby West African countries account for the largest percentage of the immigrant population.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In the 21st century, a few thousand people from Europe and the Americas have settled in the country, mostly professionals, entrepreneurs, and retirees.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Over 22,000 foreign-born residents are naturalized, hailing from over 90 countries.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The infant mortality rate among children between 0 and 5 years old is 15 per 1,000 live births according to the latest (2017) data from the National Statistics Bureau, while the maternal mortality rate is 42 deaths per 100,000 live births.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The HIV-AIDS prevalence rate among Cape Verdeans between 15 and 49 years old is 0.8%.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] According to the latest data (2017) from the National Statistics Bureau, life expectancy at birth is 76.2 years; that is, 72.2 years for males and 80.2 years for females.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] There are six hospitals: two central hospitals (Praia and Mindelo) and four regional hospitals (in Santa Catarina, São Antão, Fogo, and Sal).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In addition, there are 28 health centres, 35 sanitation centres, and a variety of private clinics.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The population is among the healthiest in Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Since its independence, it has greatly improved its health indicators.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Besides having been promoted to the group of "medium development" countries in 2007, leaving the least developed countries category (becoming the second country to do so), as of 2020 it was the 11th best ranked country in Africa in its Human Development Index.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The total expenditure on health was 7.1% of GDP (2015).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cabo Verde ranks 48th out of 127 countries with sufficient data, with a GHI score of 9.2, indicating low hunger.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde has one of the best educational systems in Africa, ranked 8th by the World Education Forum in 2023.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Primary school education is mandatory and free for children between ages 6–14.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2011, the net enrolment ratio for primary school was 85%.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Approximately 91% of the total population over 15 years of age is literate, and roughly 25% of the population holds a college degree; a significant number of these college graduates hold doctorate degrees in different academic fields.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Textbooks have been made available to 90 percent of school children, and 98 percent of the teachers have attended in-service teacher training.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Although most children have access to education, some problems remain.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] For example, there is insufficient spending on school materials, lunches, and books.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As of October 2016, there were 69 secondary schools (including 19 private secondary schools) and at least 10 universities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2015, 23% of the population had either attended or graduated from secondary schools.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] When it came to higher education, 9% of men and 8% of women held a bachelor's degree or had attended universities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The total expenditure on education was 5.6% of GDP (2010).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The mean number of years of schooling among adults over 25 years was 12.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde stands out in West Africa for the quality and inclusiveness of its higher education system.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As of 2017, one in four young people attended university and one-third of students opted for fields of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Women made up one-third of students but two-thirds of graduates in 2018.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2011, Cape Verde devoted just 0.07% of its GDP to research and development, among the lowest rates in West Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The Ministry of Higher Education, Science and Culture plan to strengthen the research and academic sectors by emphasizing greater mobility, through exchange programmes and international cooperation agreements.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] As part of this strategy, Cape Verde is participating in the Ibero-American academic mobility programme that expects to mobilize 200,000 academics between 2015 and 2020.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde was ranked 95th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde counted 25 researchers in 2011, a researcher density of 51 per million inhabitants.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The world average was 1,083 per million in 2013.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] All 25 researchers were working in the government sector in 2011 and one in three were women (36%).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] There was no research being conducted in either medical or agricultural sciences.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Of the eight engineers involved in research and development, one was a woman.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Three of the five researchers working in natural sciences were women, as were three of the six social scientists and two of the five researchers from the humanities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] In 2015, the government announced a project to build a technology park for business, research, and development.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Named TechPark Cabo Verde, operations began in 2023, and the technology park had its official inauguration in 2025.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The project is funded by both the African Development Bank and the government of Cape Verde.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The goal of the endeavour, according to Minister of Finance Olavo Correia, is "to attract large international companies to set up shop [in order] to help local companies and start-ups become more competitive".
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Cape Verde has a high rate of Internet penetration and a growing mobile phone market.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The government has invested in improving ICT infrastructure and has created a number of initiatives to promote the development of the digital economy.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] The digital economy has the potential to create jobs, boost economic growth, and improve the quality of life.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Theft and burglary are common, especially in crowded environments such as marketplaces, festivals, and celebrations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Often the perpetrators of these crimes are gangs of street children.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p01] Murders are concentrated in the major population centres of Praia and Mindelo.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The culture of Cape Verde is characterized by a mixture of African and European elements, while the language and religion are of European origin, several other aspects, such as dance and music, are a unique blend of the cultural heritage of the two different continents.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Football games and church activities are typical sources of social interaction and entertainment.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The traditional walk around the *praça* (town square) to meet friends is practised regularly in Cape Verdean towns.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] In towns with electricity, television is available on four channels; one state-owned (RTC – TCV) and three foreign-owned: RTI Cabo Verde launched by the Portuguese-based RTI in 2005; Record Cabo Verde, launched by the Brazilian-based Rede Record on 31 March 2007; and as of 2016, TV CPLP.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Premium channels available include the Cape Verdean versions of Boom TV and Zap Cabo Verde, two channels owned by Brazil's Record.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Other premium channels are available in Cape Verde, especially satellite network channels which are common in hotels and villas, though availability is otherwise limited.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] One such channel is RDP África, the African version of the Portuguese radio station RDP.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] As of early 2023, about 99% of the population own an active cellular phone, 70% have access to the Internet, 11% own a landline telephone, and 2% subscribe to local cable TV.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] In 2004, there were seven radio stations: six independent and one state-owned.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The media is operated by the Cape-Verdean News Agency (secondarily as Inforpress).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Nationwide radio stations include RCV, RCV+, Radio Kriola, and the religious station Radio Nova.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Local radio stations include Rádio Praia, the first radio station in Cape Verde; Praia FM, the first FM station in the nation; Rádio Barlavento, Rádio Clube do Mindelo and Radio Morabeza in Mindelo.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The Cape Verdean people are known for their musicality, well expressed by popular manifestations such as the Carnaval of Mindelo.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verdean music incorporates "African, Portuguese, and Brazilian influences." The national music is the *morna*, a melancholy and lyrical song form typically sung in Cape Verdean Creole.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The most popular music genre after *morna* is the *coladeira*, followed by *funaná* and *batuque* music.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cesária Évora was the best-known Cape Verdean singer in the world, known as the "barefoot diva", because she liked to perform barefooted on stage.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] She was also referred to as "The Queen of Morna" as opposed to her uncle Bana, who was referred to as "King of Morna".
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The Cape Verdean diaspora experience is reflected in many artistic and cultural expressions, such as Évora's song *Sodade*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Other singers include Sara Tavares, Lura and Mayra Andrade.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Another great exponent of traditional music from Cape Verde was Antonio Vicente Lopes, better known as Travadinha, and Ildo Lobo, who died in 2004.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The House of Culture in the centre of the city of Praia is called Ildo Lobo House of Culture in his honour.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The most popular dance genre is called *funaná* which originated on Santiago and is danced solo or in pairs with fast knee flexions and a lively rhythm.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Another popular dance genre is *coladeira*, a slower dance genre that originated on São Vicente.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] *Batuque* originated on Santiago and involves a lot of hip movement and percussion.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Zouk and Kizomba are newer popular dance genres that originated in other countries.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verdean literature is one of the richest of Lusophone Africa.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Poets include Paulino Vieira, Manuel de Novas, Sergio Frusoni, Eugénio Tavares, and B.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Léza, and authors include Baltasar Lopes da Silva, António Aurélio Gonçalves, Manuel Lopes, Orlanda Amarílis, Henrique Teixeira de Sousa, Arménio Vieira, Kaoberdiano Dambará, Dr.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The first novel written by a woman from Cape Verde was *A Louca de Serrano* by Dina Salústio; its translation, as *The Madwoman of Serrano,* was the first translation of any Cape Verdean novel to English.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The carnival and the island of São Vicente are portrayed in the 2015 feature documentary *Tchindas*, nominated at the 12th Africa Movie Academy Awards.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] It was the location for the 2023 French film *Ama Gloria* by Marie Amachoukeli.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verdean cuisine is mostly based on fish and staple foods like corn and rice.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Vegetables available during most of the year are potatoes, onions, tomatoes, manioc, cabbage, kale, and dried beans.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Fruits such as bananas and papayas are available year-round, while others like mangoes and avocados are seasonal.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] A popular dish is *cachupa*, a slow-cooked stew of corn (hominy), beans, and fish or meat.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] A common appetizer is the *pastel*, a pastry shell filled with fish or meat that is then fried.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The most successful sports team is the Cape Verde men's national handball team, which won the silver medal at the 2022 African Men's Handball Championship and the bronze medal at the 2026 African Men's Handball Championship.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] They made their first appearance at the African Men's Handball Championship in 2020, and they have been participating in the IHF World Men's Handball Championship since 2019.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verde is famous for wave sailing (a type of windsurfing) and kiteboarding.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Josh Angulo, a Hawaiian and 2009 PWA Wave World Champion, has done much to promote the archipelago as a windsurfing destination.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Mitu Monteiro, a local kite-surfer was the 2008 Kite Surfing World Champion in the wave discipline.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verde is represented by a national team in association football, nicknamed the *Tubarões Azuis* (lit.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] 'Blue Sharks'), which is controlled by the Cape Verdean Football Federation (FCF).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] It garnered further acclaim for taking reigning champions Argentina to extra time in the round of 32, ultimately losing 3–2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The women's national football team also achieved qualification to the Women's Africa Cup of Nations for the first time at the tournament's 2026 edition.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Cape Verde has competed at every Summer Olympics since 1996 but did not win its first medal until 2024, when Daniel Varela de Pina won a bronze medal in boxing.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] In 2016, Gracelino Barbosa became the first Cape Verdean to win a medal at the Paralympic Games.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] There are four international ports: Mindelo, Praia, Palmeira, and Sal Rei.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Mindelo on São Vicente is the main port for cruise ships and the terminus for the ferry service to Santo Antão.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Praia on Santiago is the main hub for local ferry services to other islands.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Palmeira on Sal supplies fuel for the main airport on the island, Amílcar Cabral International Airport, and is important for the hotel construction taking place on the island.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Porto Novo on Santo Antão is the only source for imports and exports of produce from the island, as well as passenger traffic, since the closure of the airstrip at Ponta do Sol.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] There are smaller harbours, essentially single jetties at Tarrafal on São Nicolau, Sal Rei on Boa Vista, Vila do Maio (Porto Inglês) on Maio, São Filipe on Fogo and Furna on Brava.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] These act as terminals for the inter-island ferry services, which carry both freight and passengers.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] The pier at Santa Maria on Sal, used by both fishing and dive boats, has been rehabilitated.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] There were seven operational airports as of 2014 – four international and three domestic.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Two others were non-operational, one on Brava and the other on Santo Antão closed for safety reasons.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Due to its geographical location, Cape Verde is often flown over by transatlantic airliners.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] It is part of the conventional air traffic route from Europe to South America, which goes from southern Portugal via the Canary Islands and Cape Verde to northern Brazil.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verde-p02] Small unmanned flying drones able to carry up to 5 kg (11 lb) were being used experimentally for tasks such as delivering medicines between the islands in 2021.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verdian-sign-language] In 2010, a school for children who are deaf was established in Cape Verde.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/cape-verdian-sign-language] Another deaf school was also established in Praia.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Eritrea underwent a series of colonization, lasting almost four centuries, from the Ottoman Empire, the British Empire, and the Italian Empire, though not resulting in significant linguistic influences in EriSL.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] It formally developed out of the Swedish and Finnish Sign Languages, which were introduced by Swedish and Finnish Christian missionaries in 1955, containing a certain amount of local Eritrean home signs, and having ASL-based Sudanese influences.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Ethiopian sign language did not affect the development of EriSL, given its formal introduction not earlier than 20 years after the advancements of Eritrean Sign Language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The heterogeneity of sign language acquisition in Eritrea is significantly influenced by the limited education available in more remote areas of the country.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This limits not only the contact and social engagement that the Deaf community is commonly prone to but also the sense of Deaf identity that forms consequent to proximity and exposure to other Deaf individuals.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Prior to the founding of schools for the deaf in Keren and Asmara, there is no documented evidence of indigenous signs.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] A Swedish missionary in 1945 meeting three deaf children led to the establishment of a class for deaf children in 1955.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] In 1957, with funding from Finnish missionaries, a school called "Evangelical Church School for the Deaf, Keren" was founded.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Swedish-Finnish Signs were taught in the school.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] During the war between Eritrea and Ethiopia from 1962 to 1991, Deaf education was moved from Keren to Asmara.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] In 1980 the Deaf community returned to Keren.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] A permanent school was established in Asmara, in 1988, a day school, while the one in Keren is a residential program.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] There was variation between the signing of students of the two schools.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The mission influence on Eritrean Sign Language was present from the start of deaf education.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The students were taught using Swedish and Finnish Signs.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] These instructors left Eritrea following the rising conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia in the 1970s.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Two Eritrean teachers, Neguyse and Besserat Tekleab, filled the role left by the foreign instructors.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] They changed the pedagogical approach, instructing the students in the Tigrinya, the native spoken language of Eritrea.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Another major pedagogical change to the instruction of deaf students was the introduction of Manual Ge'ez.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Ge'ez is the script used to write Tigrinya, and other languages used in Eritrea and Ethiopia.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This fingerspelling system was developed by neighboring Ethiopia in 1979 and introduced to Eritrean Deaf education the same year.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This fingerspelling system allowed deaf Eritreans to communicate in Tigrinya, greatly expanding their communicative reach.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The Eritrea National Association of the Deaf (EriNAD), established in 1998 in Asmara, provided the community with their first handbook of EriSL basic signs to spread a more uniform language education nationwide.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The first official dictionary was conceived in 2006, completed in 2009, and published in 2010 under the counsel of EriNAD.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This handpicked encyclopedia contained signs recognized as the most commonly used, considering many home signs brought forward by the collectives representing larger villages from the six regions of Eritrea.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] EriNAD was significantly influential in promoting the advocacy and participation of EriSL interpreters in various institutions (academic, work-related, etc.), thereby fostering further Deaf inclusivity in a predominantly hearing society.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This latter has been a topic of discussion for many years, given the deeply felt unequal placement in a convoluted social stratification system, such as the one present in Eritrea concerning disabled people.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] An example of a rejected agency occurred due to the Ministry of Education (Special Needs Department) 's avoidance of designing, crafting, and actualizing the language by the Deaf community.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] No authority was given to them, even though this would later become their native language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Approximately 70% of the signs used in Eritrean Sign Language (EriSL) are identical to those found in Finnish Sign Language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This overlap is largely a result of the influence of Finnish and Swedish missionaries who were instrumental in the early development of deaf education in Eritrea.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] However, since 2005, the Eritrean National Association of the Deaf has been actively working to remove Finnish and Swedish signs that do not align with Eritrean cultural expressions or vernacular usage.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] In their place, the Association has been incorporating indigenous village signs, gestures, and expressions that are rooted in the everyday communication of local Deaf communities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] This intentional effort signifies a process of "demissionizing" EriSL, which entails removing missionary influence to restore linguistic ownership and autonomy.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] It emphasizes the distinct cultural and national identity of Eritrea, setting it apart from the Nordic origins of the earlier sign systems.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The initiative highlights how Deaf identity is not monolithic ("Deaf-same") but shaped by unique cultural and historical contexts.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] As part of this process, the Eritrean Deaf community has also been working on creating a new version of sign encyclopedia, a more culturally grounded one.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] A dictionary that reflects Eritrean values, traditions, and lived experiences, and serves not only as a linguistic resource but also as a symbol of cultural affirmation and self-determination.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Prior to the demissionization process, Eritrean Sign Language was heavily influenced by many factors, such as globalization, Swedish and Finnish linguistic imperialism during the era of missionization, and oralist methodologies.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Alongside colonial signs and gestures, the d/Deaf community was also influenced by oralist methodology provided by the foreign missionaries and teachers.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Globalization is another factor that plays a role within the deaf communities of Eritrea, bringing about modernity that impacts on the Deaf community's rural and urban factions, affecting not only their perspectives on their own deaf identity, but also their viewpoint on sign language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] One aspect of globalization is the missionization of Eritrean sign language by the Swedish and Finnish missionaries; they are imposing their sign language onto the community that has an already developed, indigenous sign language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Following the process of demissionization, though it is still an ongoing process, we see a shift in not only pedagogy and the signs themselves, but also a shift in the perspectives and ideologies within the d/Deaf Eritrean community.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] In Sub-Saharan Africa, there is a wide range of d/Deaf identities and diverse perspectives on deafness – most of which lead to increased isolation and marginalization of the deaf individuals and communities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The diversity of the perspectives of deafness and the diversity of language isn't limited to the whole of Sub-Saharan Africa, but is also significantly prevalent within Eritrea, particularly between the urban and rural deaf populations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Different settings (rural versus urban), with the included factor of globalization, produce different perspectives on demissionization and attempts at language purism.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Rezenet Tsegay Moges-Riedel is a deaf, American-Eritrean anthropologist, currently teaching as an assistant professor of American Sign Language and Deaf Culture at California State University Long Beach.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Moges-Riedel began her ethnographic research in 2006; completed her Master's thesis on “Demissionization through Sign Language Dictionary-Making Process in Deaf Eritrean Community,” and received her master's degree in 2011.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] She received her EdD in Education and Leadership Policy Studies in 2017 from CSU Northridge.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Her research focuses on the spread and documentation of language, linguistic imperialism and sign language contact, language ideology and language purism.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] She is fluent in EriSL, ASL and Irish Sign Language, and an expert on d/Deaf identity and Intersectionality.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Throughout her academic career, she has taught many courses on sign language and Deaf culture, released many publications pertinent to her research, as well as professional interests, particularly pertaining to African Deaf communities and Deaf cultures.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] She has also given speeches and lectures at various universities and anthropological research symposiums around the world, including the U.S., Canada, London, Edinburgh, Brazil, Belgium, Germany, the Netherlands, Denmark, South Africa and Turkey.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Moges-Riedel's contribution to researching the Eritrean Deaf community and its sign language, as well as understanding the colonial, sociocultural and political influences that have shaped the language and experiences, is revolutionary to understanding more about them.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] The establishment of the Eritrean Deaf community, and its official form of communication are so relatively new, (so new that even Eritrean websites and resources still aren't entirely up to date yet) that Dr.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Moges-Riedel's work has provided a significant foundation for further understanding and development, and her research is the primary source of information on Eritrean deaf communities and EriSL.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Due to her focus, research interests and personal background, Dr.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/eritrean-sign-language] Moges-Riedel's research provides a diverse, yet comprehensive, perspective on Eritrean deaf culture and language shaped by both her ethnographic fieldwork and her personal experiences as a deaf, Eritrean, anthropologist.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] The first deaf school in Finland was founded in 1846 by Carl Oscar Malm, who was deaf himself.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] Since the closure of the deaf school in Borgå in 1993, the future of the language has been uncertain.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] Many families with deaf children have emigrated to Sweden because of the decision.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] The language is considered severely endangered according to UNESCO's criteria.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] Since 2015, Finland-Swedish and Finnish sign languages have been recognized as separate languages in Finnish legislation, as the new sign language act was adopted in the parliament.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] However, the scientific consensus has been since 2005 that the two sign languages are distinct.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] Through contacts between Swedish deaf individuals and Finland-Swedish deaf individuals, the Finland-Swedish sign language has borrowed many words from Swedish sign language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finland-swedish-sign-language] Additionally, the visual phonology with facial expressions follows the sounds of the Swedish language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Finnish legislation recognized Finnish Sign Language as one of Finland's domestic languages in 1995 when it was included in the renewed constitution.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Finland then became the third country in the world to recognize a sign language as a natural language and the right to use it as a mother tongue.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Courses in "sign language" have been taught in Finland since the 1960s.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] At that time, instruction taught signs but followed Finnish word order (see Manually Coded Language).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Later, as research on sign languages in general and Finnish Sign Language in particular determined that sign languages tend to have a very different grammar from oral languages, the teaching of Finnish Sign Language and Signed Finnish diverged.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Finnish Sign Language can be traced back to the mid-1800s when Carl Oscar Malm, a Finnish deaf individual who had studied in Sweden, founded Finland's first school for the deaf in Porvoo in 1846.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] The Swedish sign language used by Malm spread among Finnish deaf individuals, evolving into its own language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] The first association for the deaf in Finland was established in Turku in 1886.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Albert Tallroth was involved in founding five different deaf associations and also the Finnish Association of the Deaf.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] By the late 1800s, oralism, or the speech method, began to be favored in the education of the deaf in Finland.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] This led to the prohibition of sign language in schools, even under threat of punishment.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] And as a result of oralism, Finnish Sign Language and Finnish-Swedish Sign Language began to diverge.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Despite the ban, students in deaf schools continued to use sign language secretly in dormitories.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] The use of sign language persisted within the deaf community, while spoken language learned in school was used when interacting with hearing individuals.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Society started to have a more positive attitude towards the deaf and sign language after the 1970s.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Sign language became a tool for rehabilitation and education, and it began to be taught in courses for parents of deaf children.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] In 1979, interpreter services became part of disability legislation, and in 1995, sign language gained constitutional status.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] In 1991, the possibility of sign language education was written into the Basic Education Act.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Sign language can be studied as a major at the University of Jyväskylä.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Additionally, it has been possible to complete basic studies in sign language and communication at the University of Turku.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] One can study to become a sign language instructor at Pohjois-Savo Folk High School in Kuopio, at Rovala-Opisto in Rovaniemi, and at Turku Christian Institute.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/finnish-sign-language] Finnish Sign Language can be studied at the Finnish Association of the Deaf Folk High School, adult education centers, and summer universities.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] An **IETF BCP 47 language tag** is a standardized code that is used to identify human languages on the Internet.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The tag structure has been standardized by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in *Best Current Practice (BCP) 47*; the subtags are maintained by the *IANA Language Subtag Registry*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] To distinguish language variants for countries, regions, or writing systems (scripts), IETF language tags combine subtags from other standards such as ISO 639, ISO 15924, ISO 3166-1 and UN M.49.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] It is used by computing standards such as HTTP, HTML, XML and PNG.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] IETF language tags were first defined in Request for comment 1766, edited by Harald Tveit Alvestrand, published in March 1995.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The tags used ISO 639 two-letter language codes and ISO 3166 two-letter country codes, and allowed registration of whole tags that included variant or script subtags of three to eight letters.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] In January 2001, this was updated by RFC 3066, which added the use of ISO 639-2 three-letter codes, permitted subtags with digits, and adopted the concept of language ranges from HTTP/1.1 to help with matching of language tags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The next revision of the specification came in September 2006 with the publication of RFC 4646—the main part of the specification—edited by Addison Philips and Mark Davis, and RFC 4647—which deals with matching behaviour.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] RFC 4646 introduced a more structured format for language tags, added the use of ISO 15924 four-letter script codes and UN M.49 three-digit geographical region codes, and replaced the old registry of tags with a new registry of subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The small number of previously defined tags that did not conform to the new structure were grandfathered in order to maintain compatibility with RFC 3066.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The current version of the specification, RFC 5646, was published in September 2009.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The main purpose of this revision was to incorporate three-letter codes from ISO 639-3 and 639-5 into the Language Subtag Registry, in order to increase the interoperability between ISO 639 and BCP 47.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Each language tag is composed of one or more "subtags" separated by hyphens (-).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Each subtag is composed only of either basic Latin letters or digits.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Subtags are not case-sensitive, but the specification recommends using the same case as in the Language Subtag Registry, where region subtags are UPPERCASE, script subtags are title case, and all other subtags are lowercase.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] This capitalization follows the recommendations of the underlying ISO standards.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Optional script and region subtags are preferred to be omitted when they add no distinguishing information to a language tag.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, *es* is preferred over *es-Latn*, as Spanish is fully expected to be written in the Latin script; *ja* is preferred over *ja-JP*, as Japanese *as used in Japan* does not differ markedly from Japanese as used elsewhere.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Not all linguistic regions can be represented with a valid region subtag: the subnational regional dialects of a primary language are registered as variant subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, the *valencia* variant subtag for the Valencian variant of the Catalan is registered in the Language Subtag Registry with the prefix *ca*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] As this dialect is spoken almost exclusively in Spain, the region subtag *ES* can normally be omitted.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Furthermore, there are script tags that do not refer to traditional scripts such as Latin, or even scripts at all, and these usually begin with a *Z.* For example, *Zsye* refers to emojis, *Zmth* to mathematical notation, *Zxxx* to unwritten documents and *Zyyy* to undetermined scripts.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] IETF language tags have been used as locale identifiers in many applications.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] It may be necessary for these applications to establish their own strategy for defining, encoding and matching locales if the strategy described in RFC 4647 is not adequate.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The use, interpretation and matching of IETF language tags is currently defined in RFC 5646 and RFC 4647.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The Language Subtag Registry lists all currently valid public subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Private-use subtags are not included in the Registry as they are implementation-dependent and subject to private agreements between third parties using them.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] These private agreements are out of scope of BCP 47.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The following is a list of some of the more commonly used primary language subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The list represents only a small subset (less than 2 percent) of primary language subtags; for full information, the Language Subtag Registry should be consulted directly.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Although some types of subtags are derived from ISO or UN core standards, they do not follow these standards absolutely, as this could lead to the meaning of language tags changing over time.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] In particular, a subtag derived from a code assigned by ISO 639, ISO 15924, ISO 3166, or UN M49 remains a valid (though deprecated) subtag even if the code is withdrawn from the corresponding core standard.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] If the standard later assigns a new meaning to the withdrawn code, the corresponding subtag will still retain its old meaning.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] This stability was introduced in RFC 4646.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] RFC 4646 defined the concept of an "extended language subtag" (sometimes referred to as *extlang*), although no such subtags were registered at that time.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] RFC 5645 and RFC 5646 added primary language subtags corresponding to ISO 639-3 codes for all languages that did not already exist in the Registry.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] In addition, codes for languages encompassed by certain macrolanguages were registered as extended language subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Sign languages were also registered as extlangs, with the prefix *sgn*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] These languages may be represented either with the subtag for the encompassed language alone (*cmn* for Mandarin) or with a language-extlang combination (*zh-cmn*).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The first option is preferred for most purposes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The second option is called "extlang form" and is new in RFC 5646.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Whole tags that were registered prior to RFC 4646 and are now classified as "grandfathered" or "redundant" (depending on whether they fit the new syntax) are deprecated in favor of the corresponding ISO 639-3–based language subtag, if one exists.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] To list a few examples, *nan* is preferred over *zh-min-nan* for Min Nan Chinese; *hak* is preferred over *i-hak* and *zh-hakka* for Hakka Chinese; and *ase* is preferred over *sgn-US* for American Sign Language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Windows Vista and later versions of Microsoft Windows have RFC 4646 support.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-5 defines language collections with alpha-3 codes in a different way than they were initially encoded in ISO 639-2 (including one code already present in ISO 639-1, Bihari coded inclusively as *bh* in ISO 639-1 and *bih* in ISO 639-2).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Specifically, the language collections are now all defined in ISO 639-5 as inclusive, rather than some of them being defined exclusively.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] This means that language collections have a broader scope than before, in some cases where they could encompass languages that were already encoded separately within ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, the ISO 639-2 code *afa* was previously associated with the name "Afro-Asiatic (Other)", excluding languages such as Arabic that already had their own code.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] In ISO 639-5, this collection is named "Afro-Asiatic languages" and includes all such languages.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-2 changed the exclusive names in 2009 to match the inclusive ISO 639-5 names.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] BCP 47 defines a "Scope" property to identify subtags for language collections.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] However, it does not define any given collection as inclusive or exclusive, and does not use the ISO 639-5 grouping type attribute, although the description fields in the Language Subtag Registry for these subtags match the ISO 639-5 (inclusive) names.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] As a consequence, BCP 47 language tags that include a primary language subtag for a collection may be ambiguous as to whether the collection is intended to be inclusive or exclusive.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] ISO 639-5 does not define precisely which languages are members of these collections; only the hierarchical classification of collections is defined, using the inclusive definition of these collections.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Because of this, RFC 5646 does not recommend the use of subtags for language collections for most applications, although they are still preferred over subtags whose meaning is even less specific, such as "Multiple languages" and "Undetermined".
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] In contrast, the classification of individual languages within their macrolanguage is standardized, in both ISO 639-3 and the Language Subtag Registry.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Script subtags were first added to the Language Subtag Registry when RFC 4646 was published, from the list of codes defined in ISO 15924.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] They are encoded in the language tag after primary and extended language subtags, but before other types of subtag, including region and variant subtags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Some primary language subtags are defined with a property named "Suppress-Script" which indicates the cases where a single script can usually be assumed by default for the language, even if it can be written with another script.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] When this is the case, it is preferable to omit the script subtag, to improve the likelihood of successful matching.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] A different script subtag can still be appended to make the distinction when necessary.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, *yi* is preferred over *yi-Hebr* in most contexts, because the Hebrew script subtag is assumed for the Yiddish language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] As another example, *zh-Hans-SG* may be considered equivalent to *zh-Hans*, because the region code is probably not significant; the written form of Chinese used in Singapore uses the same simplified Chinese characters as in other countries where Chinese is written.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] However, the script subtag is maintained because it is significant.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] ISO 15924 includes some codes for script variants (for example, *Hans* and *Hant* for simplified and traditional forms of Chinese characters) that are unified within Unicode and ISO/IEC 10646.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] They may occasionally be useful in language tags to expose orthographic or semantic differences, with different analysis of letters, diacritics, and digraphs/trigraphs as default grapheme clusters, or differences in letter casing rules.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Two-letter region subtags are based on codes assigned, or "exceptionally reserved", in ISO 3166-1.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] If the ISO 3166 Maintenance Agency were to reassign a code that had previously been assigned to a different country, the existing BCP 47 subtag corresponding to that code would retain its meaning, and a new region subtag based on UN M.49 would be registered for the new country.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] UN M.49 is also the source for numeric region subtags for geographical regions, such as `005` for South America.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The UN M.49 codes for economic regions are not allowed.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Region subtags are used to specify the variety of a language "as used in" a particular region.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] They are appropriate when the variety is regional in nature, and can be captured adequately by identifying the countries involved, as when distinguishing British English (*en-GB*) from American English (*en-US*).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] When the difference is one of script or script variety, as for simplified versus traditional Chinese characters, it should be expressed with a script subtag instead of a region subtag; in this example, *zh-Hans* and *zh-Hant* should be used instead of *zh-CN/zh-SG/zh-MY* and *zh-TW/zh-HK/zh-MO*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] When a distinct language subtag exists for a language that could be considered a regional variety, it is often preferable to use the more specific subtag instead of a language-region combination.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, *ar-DZ* (Arabic as used in Algeria) may be better expressed as *arq* for Algerian Spoken Arabic.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Disagreements about language identification may extend to BCP 47 and to the core standards that inform it.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] BCP 47 delegates this type of judgment to the core standards, and does not attempt to overrule or supersede them.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Variant subtags and (theoretically) primary language subtags may be registered individually, but not in a way that contradicts the core standards.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Extension subtags are composed of multiple hyphen-separated character strings, starting with a single character (other than *x*), called a *singleton*.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Each extension is described in its own IETF RFC, which identifies a Registration Authority to manage the data for that extension.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] IANA is responsible for allocating singletons.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Two extensions have been assigned as of January 2014.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Extension T allows a language tag to include information on how the tagged data was transliterated, transcribed, or otherwise transformed.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] For example, the tag *en-t-jp* could be used for content in English that was translated from the original Japanese.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Additional substrings could indicate that the translation was done mechanically, or in accordance with a published standard.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Extension T is described in the informational RFC 6497, published in February 2012.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] The Registration Authority is the Unicode Consortium.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Extension U allows a wide variety of locale attributes found in the Common Locale Data Repository (CLDR) to be embedded in language tags.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Extension U is described in the informational RFC 6067, published in December 2010.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/ietf-language-tag] Its LDML specification, published as UTS 35, serves as the documentation of registered attributes and keywords.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] As of 2023, this edition of the standard has been officially withdrawn and replaced by ISO 639:2023.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-3 extends the ISO 639-2 alpha-3 codes with an aim to cover all known natural languages.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The extended language coverage was based primarily on the language codes used in the *Ethnologue* (volumes 10–14) published by SIL International, which is now the registration authority for ISO 639-3.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] It provides an enumeration of languages as complete as possible, including living and extinct, ancient and constructed, major and minor, written and unwritten.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] However, it does not include reconstructed languages such as Proto-Indo-European.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-3 is intended for use as metadata codes in a wide range of applications.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] It is widely used in computer and information systems, such as the Internet, in which many languages need to be supported.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] In archives and other information storage, it is used in cataloging systems, indicating what language a resource is in or about.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The codes are also frequently used in the linguistic literature and elsewhere to compensate for the fact that language names may be obscure or ambiguous.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-3 includes all languages in ISO 639-1 and all individual languages in ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-1 and ISO 639-2 focused on major languages, most frequently represented in the total body of the world's literature.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Since ISO 639-2 also includes language collections and Part 3 does not, ISO 639-3 is not a superset of ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Where B and T codes exist in ISO 639-2, ISO 639-3 uses the T-codes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] As of 23 January 2023, the standard contains 7,916 entries.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Machine-readable data files are provided by the registration authority.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Mappings from ISO 639-1 or ISO 639-2 to ISO 639-3 can be done using these data files.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-3 is intended to assume distinctions based on criteria that are not entirely objective.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] It is not intended to document or provide identifiers for dialects or other sub-language variations.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Nevertheless, judgments regarding distinctions between languages may be subjective, particularly in the case of language varieties without established literary traditions, usage in education or media, or other factors that contribute to language conventionalization.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Therefore, the standard should not be regarded as an authoritative statement of what distinct languages exist in the world (about which there may be substantial disagreement in some cases), but rather simply one useful way for identifying different language varieties precisely.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Since the code is three-letter alphabetic, one upper bound for the number of languages that can be represented is 26 × 26 × 26 = 17,576.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Since ISO 639-2 defines special codes (4), a reserved range (520) and B-only codes (22), 546 codes cannot be used in part 3.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The upper bound gets even stricter if one subtracts the language collections defined in 639-2 and the ones yet to be defined in ISO 639-5.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Reference names may only use a subset of ASCII characters.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Reference names may also include any of five ASCII punctuation marks (space, hyphen-minus, apostrophe and the parentheses), and within parentheses the full stop and the ten digits.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Alternative names may use proper language orthography, if Latin, or transliteration into Latin script that contains additional characters.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] There are 58 languages in ISO 639-2 which are considered, for the purposes of the standard, to be "macrolanguages" in ISO 639-3.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Some of these macrolanguages had no individual language as defined by ISO 639-3 in the code set of ISO 639-2, e.g.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Others like `nor` (Norwegian) had their two individual parts (`nno` (Nynorsk), `nob` (Bokmål)) already in ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] `arb`, Standard Arabic) that were considered by ISO 639-2 to be dialects of one language (`ara`) are now in ISO 639-3 in certain contexts considered to be individual languages themselves.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] This is an attempt to deal with varieties that may be linguistically distinct from each other, but are treated by their speakers as two forms of the same language, e.g. in cases of diglossia.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] A complete list is available on the ISO 639-3 registrar's website.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] "A collective language code element is an identifier that represents a group of individual languages that are not deemed to be one language in any usage context." These codes do not precisely represent a particular language or macrolanguage.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] While ISO 639-2 includes three-letter identifiers for collective languages, these codes are excluded from ISO 639-3.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Hence ISO 639-3 is not a superset of ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] ISO 639-5 defines 3-letter collective codes for language families and groups, including the collective language codes from ISO 639-2.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Four codes are set aside in ISO 639-2 and ISO 639-3 for cases where none of the specific codes are appropriate.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] These are intended primarily for applications like databases where an ISO code is required regardless of whether one exists.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] In addition, 520 codes in the range `qaa`–`qtz` are 'reserved for local use'.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] For example, Rebecca Bettencourt assigns a code to constructed languages, and new assignments are made upon request.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The code table for ISO 639-3 is open to changes.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The code assigned to a language is not changed unless there is also a change in denotation.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Changes are made according to an annual cycle.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Every request is given a minimum period of three months for public review.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The ISO 639-3 Web site has pages that describe "scopes of denotation" (languoid types) and types of languages, which explain what concepts are in scope for encoding and certain criteria that need to be met.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] For example, constructed languages can be encoded, but only if they are designed for human communication and have a body of literature, preventing requests for idiosyncratic inventions.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] The registration authority documents on its Web site instructions made in the text of the ISO 639-3 standard regarding how the code tables are to be maintained.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] It also documents the processes used for receiving and processing change requests.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] A change request form is provided, and there is a second form for collecting information about proposed additions.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] When submitted, requests are initially reviewed by the registration authority for completeness.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] When a fully documented request is received, it is added to a published Change Request Index.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Also, announcements are sent to the general LINGUIST discussion list at Linguist List and other lists the registration authority may consider relevant, inviting public review and input on the requested change.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Any list owner or individual is able to request notifications of change requests for particular regions or language families.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Comments that are received are published for other parties to review.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Based on consensus in comments received, a change request may be withdrawn or promoted to "candidate status".
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Three months prior to the end of an annual review cycle (typically in September), an announcement is sent to the LINGUIST discussion list and other lists regarding Candidate Status Change Requests.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] All requests remain open for review and comment through the end of the annual review cycle.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Decisions are announced at the end of the annual review cycle (typically in January).
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] At that time, requests may be adopted in whole or in part, amended and carried forward into the next review cycle, or rejected.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Rejections often include suggestions on how to modify proposals for resubmission.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] A public archive of every change request is maintained along with the decisions taken and the rationale for the decisions.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] Martin Haspelmath agrees with four of these points, but not the point about language change.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] He disagrees because any account of a language requires identifying it, and we can easily identify different stages of a language.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] He cites the original need for standardized language identifiers as having been "the economic significance of translation and software localization", for which purposes the ISO 639-1 and 639-2 standards were established.
[src:cape-verdian-sign-language/iso-639-3] But he raises doubts about industry need for the comprehensive coverage provided by ISO 639-3, including as it does "little-known languages of small communities that are never or hardly used in writing and that are often in danger of extinction".
